Bring a #saucepan{} of @water{} to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp} for the noodles.

When boiling, add the @egg noodle nest{2} and bring back to the boil. Cook until
tender, ~{4%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{}. 

> TIP: Run the noodles under cold water to stop them sticking together.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} or #wok{} on
medium-high heat.

When hot, add the @chicken breast{260%g}(diced) and season with salt and
@pepper{}. Fry, stirring occasionally, until browned, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Meanwhile, halve the @plum{2}, remove the stones and chop each half into three
wedges.

Trim the @pak choi{1} then thinly slice widthways.

Trim and thinly slice the @spring onion{1}.

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Lower the heat to medium and add the plums and @sugar{1%tsp} to the pan with
the chicken.

Stir-fry until the plums start to colour, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in the garlic and @ginger puree{1/2%tsp} along with half the spring onion
and as many @chilli flakes{1} as you like (careful - they're hot).

Stir-fry for another ~{1%minute}.

Add the bok choy and stir-fry until just soft, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in the @hoisin sauce{32%g}, @ketjap manis{25%ml} and @water{25%ml}, ensuring
everything is well coated.

Add the cooked noodles to the pan. Stir together and cook until everything is
piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Divide the chicken and plum stir-fry between your bowls.

Scatter over the @salted peanuts{25%g} and remaining spring onion to serve.
Enjoy!

> Step 2 MOD: If you've chosen to get chicken breast instead of chicken thigh,
> cook the recipe in the same way the instructions tell you to cook the
> chicken thigh.